The economic impact assessment from 2001 was based on the assumption that the section close to the border and the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains would be subject to traffic at the same time.
At the time of the examination, it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian mountains would not be opened at the original date.
This reduces the above-mentioned EIRR values.
As of 31 December 2005, the cost of both sections amounted to €897 million excluding VAT, which is 27.4% higher than the cost-effectiveness assessment in 2001.
In addition, there is a risk that section 0805 will have a different, more complex course of action, which would affect the cost-effectiveness of the project.
The economic assessment showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway with a daily traffic volume of at least 18,000 vehicles per day in 2010 was economically justified. The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22,940 vehicles per day.
However, a study on diverting routes as an alternative to the missing section of the Bohemian Central Mountains is based on a traffic volume of between 12,600 and 13,750 vehicles per day in 2007.
A higher volume of traffic on the routes to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Central Mountains is highly likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the original economic impact assessment.
The mentioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the cross-border section of the D 8 will not be achieved.
The construction of the borderline section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomical.
There have also been cost increases in the construction of the A 17, as in the construction of the two above-mentioned sections of the D 8.
As part of the overall economic assessment for the 1992 Federal Transport Plan, the Federal Ministry of Transport estimated investment costs of around €320 million.
As a result, it calculated a benefit / cost ratio of 4.6.
In the meantime, the costs have increased to around €670 million and the benefit / cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.
The BRH had examined the cost-effectiveness of the planning and construction of the A 17 motorway in the years 2003 to 2005, regardless of the parallel tests with the NK.
He noted that the authority responsible for the approval called for an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A17.
In the course of the examination, the BRH was able to convince the Federal Ministry and the Road Construction Administration of the superfluity of the landscape tunnel.
As a result, €10 million in construction costs and €150,000 in annual operating costs could be avoided.
During the examination of the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction work was not sufficiently prepared.
This is illustrated by the following example:
During the planning phase, the road management did not allow the state of the rock to be recorded on the surface of the Dölzschener wall, as it was difficult to access.
It wasn't until the tunnel propulsion reached the wall that she picked it up.
It turned out that the rock was more weathered than was assumed at the tender.
Complex measures such as anchorages, injections and stoneware protection networks for around €3.3 million were required.
The road construction administration not only paid the costs for additional services, which were already required, such as securing the Dölzschener wall, but also for those that would not have been required in the event of a flawless construction preparation.
These include expenses as a result of disrupted construction processes (€3.2 million), additional training for the drive team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of construction time (€7 million).
This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million is not matched by any lasting added value.
The BRH took these and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to make better use of the specialist supervision for large-scale road construction measures.
In this context, it should insist on the introduction of quality assurance systems by road authorities.
The benefits of the cooperation for BRH and NK The cooperation met the expectations of both audit bodies.
The BRH received insights into the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.
Both audit bodies developed a database on bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful in future audits.
The NAC found that the most important structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and tracks of the D 8 were not different from those of the A 17.
The auditors of both audit institutions involved in the collaboration have gained valuable experience, which will be useful in future audits.
